  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework titled 'Uncertainty-Guided Dual Decoupling with Iterative Denoising' (UDID) for semi-supervised object detection, which fundamentally rethinks how clean and noisy pseudo-boxes are separated during training. Unlike existing methods that use fixed confidence thresholds to partition pseudo-labels—a process prone to error due to model overconfidence or distribution shifts—our method introduces a dynamic, learnable disentanglement mechanism driven by epistemic uncertainty estimation and iterative refinement. At the heart of UDID is a dual-path detection head: one path focuses on high-certainty (clean) instances, while the other explicitly models low-certainty (noisy) regions with adaptive regularization. Each pseudo-box is associated with an uncertainty score estimated via Monte Carlo dropout or ensemble disagreement, forming a latent cleanliness prior. Instead of discarding or down-weighting uncertain boxes immediately, we treat them as incomplete observations in a latent space and apply a lightweight iterative denoising module inspired by diffusion principles—where over successive training iterations, noisy pseudo-boxes are progressively refined toward cleaner versions using contextual cues from neighboring proposals and feature consistency across augmentations. This creates a feedback loop: early epochs focus on confidently labeled regions for stable learning, while later epochs recover suppressed yet valid objects through refinement. Additionally, we decouple classification and localization gradients based on uncertainty—allowing classification heads to learn from cleaner labels while permitting localization heads to explore uncertain spatial configurations under controlled constraints. This dual decoupling operates both architecturally and temporally, enhancing training stability and final performance. The framework is agnostic to detector backbones and can be integrated into one-stage (e.g., RetinaNet, YOLO) or two-stage (e.g